name: Black Canyon
description:
Introduction

A long backcountry adventure, navigating through slick basalt gorges, brushy streambeds, and at the end, an incredible narrows section!

Best done in class C mode. Snow up top followed by rains really gets this canyon cranking (videos below).

A few nice back country camp sites exist at the top before the technical part of the canyon. Also can be done as an upper loop or setting a shuttle at the bottom and driving up to the upper trailhead and starting there or parking up top and doing the upper loop hitting all the big raps and exiting up before or after the narrows to the main trail 114 left back up to your vehicle.

Approach

Start from upper Black Canyon trail head following obvious trail down until eventually splitting off to follow the river (reference GPS track) or hike up from the lower Black Canyon trail head.

Descent

Bushwhack and downclimb, following river to the first rap.

R1: 170' tree DCL (option to rap DCL to ledge and downclimb DCL to avoid pool or simply continue into pool)

Bushwhack and downclimb for quite a ways

R2: 90' rock wedged in crack DCR 2 stage

Bushwhack again quite a ways

R3: 140' rock chock LDC (may need to set up handline to safely access in high flow) drop into pool (pool avoidable via DCR ledge in low flow)

You now have the option to follow the obvious social trail on the left up and around to R4 or continue straight, downclimbing and sliding into the first part of the narrows which bypasses this rap.

R4: 35' bolts on wall LDC, drops down into narrows

R5: 40' bolts on wall LDC

R6: 40' tree set 20' back, 10' jump, or downclimb

R7: 25' rock pinch LDC

Exit

Hike a bit further out of the narrows, following river, then exit up canyon left (reference GPS track) Follow faint trails up the steep slope until eventually reaching the well traveled Black Canyon Trail. From here, head West up trail to finish upper loop or East down trail for lower loop/shuttle vehicle.

Alternatively, if you set up a shuttle or did the lower loop, you can decide to continue following the river all the way out to your vehicle rather than scrambling up to Black Canyon Trail (reference GPS track).
